# Game-Theoretic Probability and the Emergence of Probability

I’ve spent nearly the whole of my PhD understanding “probability,” and these have been some of the most intellectually rich years I’ve lived.  But despite my best attempts to not engage with the philosophical question of what is probability, my body goes into an anxiety mode as soon as I read or hear someone use the term “probability”, “uncertainty”, “random”, etc. So I have to do the work of culling this anxiety, and I believe the game-theoretic way of understanding probability helps me a bit. In this note, I’ll try to reason why that is.

It is argued that if one wants to do probability rigorously, it has to be done measure-theoretically. And granted, measure theoretic way of doing probability absolutely is something that one needs to experience for once. But the reason measure-theoretic probability became the standard framework is because it abstracted away the word “probability” into measure, without really actually pinning out what it is, and what meaning does it carry in the real-world. One does not deal with the philosophical question of what is probability when one does measure-theoretic probability. It is an axiomatic framework that gives rigorous calculus to reason in terms of probability when one has already committed to the meaning one wants to attach to the probability. But probabilistic reasoning is a commonplace affair partly due to the challenge of under-determinism imposed by quantum mechanics onto the Newtonian determinism. Some things cannot be known exactly, and few words that go together are things are uncertain, they are random, and probability theory allows one to reason with under-determinism rigorously. The probability of raining tomorrow is $70\%$, we say. 

Things are uncertain, things are random, and probability theory allows one to reason with under-determinism rigorously. *Random, uncertain, probable.* Well, my confusion and anxiety emerges from the blatant conflation of everything that is happening in this sentence. What I’ve really started to like and appreciate about mathematics now is how much care it takes to find good and unambiguous definitions and terminologies for basic things. But measure-theoretic probability theory, as far as I can get it, never defines these terminologies. But, they do go together colloquially along with it leading to the confusion. 

So just to give a brief overview of measure-theory: it starts with what is referred to as a measure space $(\Omega, \mathcal{F}, \mathbb{P})$. $\Omega$ is the sample space: if one is considering the event of a coin flip, it is just $\{H, T\}$, and if one is considering two coin flips consecutively, it is $\{HH, HT, TH, TT\}$. Flipping the coin (or two coins) is an experiment, and $\Omega$ denotes all the possible ways the experiment can go. $\mathcal{F}$ is referred to as the $\sigma$-algebra: it consists of possible inquiries one can make out of the results of the experiment, for example at-least one head in the two-coin tossing case $\{HH, HT, TH\}$, no tails $\{HH\}$, and hence $\mathcal{F}$ is the collection of subsets of $\Omega$ with certain properties that are not that relevant for the argument, and $\mathbb{P}$ is the probability measure that satisfies the regular axioms of probability. Given the event $E \in \mathcal{F}$, it assigns a measure to the event, e.g. $\mathbb{P}\left(\{HH, HT, TH\}\right) = \alpha$. So for the event at-least one heads, there is $\alpha \in [0,1]$ probability mass assigned. But how should one read and interpret this statement? Is it *random* the occurrence of at-least one heads, is it *uncertain* the occurrence of at-least one heads, with $\alpha$ somehow quantifying the random and the uncertain part? 

Now randomness as a word evokes a feeling that it is a property of the experiment, and by extrapolation a property of the world. And uncertain implies that it is a property of the particular experiment design. Randomness lives in the world, and uncertainty manifests in who is observing the world. We haven’t defined these terminologies, and neither did probability theory. But probability theory comes as a tool box to talk and reason about the both things without distinction. But we need to make a distinction, or at-least be aware of the terminologies and definitions. That is what mathematics is for. I reckon the [framework of game-theoretic probability as pioneered by Glenn Shafer and Vladimir Vovk](https://probabilityandfinance.com/2001_book/index.html) that builds on the work of [Bruno De Finetti](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruno_de_Finetti) and [Jean Ville](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Ville) provides the necessary resolution, or at-least side-steps the whole distinction better than measure-theory. *A one thing that I’ll base the rest of the note on is the fact that game-theoretic framework does not define probability, it emerges from the setup.* And this statement does most of the heavy-lifting to cull my anxiety, as I explain next. 

**The setup of game-theoretic probability:** The setup goes as follows: there is an experimenter who is trying to understand the world. The experimenter could be a scientist aiming to understand, say, the phenomena of coastal tides. The coastal tides represent the object of study, to understand the pattern or to predict their behaviour. As such, the coastal tides is an independent phenomena manifesting in the world out of the control of the experimenter. The experimenter can collect data, theorise based on that, and come up with some understanding of their occurrence. Such a theory is said to be good if the predictions it produces on the behaviour of the coastal tides are consistent with their behaviour. If that does not happen, the theory is bad, and the experimenter needs to do a better job.  This whole idea of observing the phenomena, collecting data to explain it, and coming up with the explanations that stay true to the phenomena, i.e. they predict well the phenomena is what the game-theoretic framework of probability is rooted in. Except it uses the word Sceptic for the experimenter, and the World for the phenomena of interest (in this case coastal tides). 

For simplicity, we are considering the data for tide (1) or no tide (0) consecutively for many days, denote this as $y_1, y_2, y_3, \ldots,$ where $y_t \in \{0,1\}$. Define $\Omega$to be the all possible sequences of tides or no-tides. This is the same sample space as before. And define a function $x: \Omega \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$, that is referred to as the variable that performs the same role as the random variable. The variable $x$ represents one possible query one asks on the the behaviour of the world (in this case the coastal tides). As an example, consider $x = 1_{E}$ for $E \subseteq \Omega$, where $E$ could denote some property worth studying like whether the tide occurs on every other day, in which case $E = \{0,1,0,1, \ldots; 1,0,1,0, \ldots\}$. This attaches this framework squarely with the scientific method outlined above. The world moves independently creating phenomena that can be observed. The Sceptic observes the data, and posits certain inquiries encoded in the variable $x$, in order to understand the phenomena. So when the Sceptic be claimed to understand the phenomena (or the world)?

Here comes, what I’d call the elegant move of this framework, and is borrowed directly from the early development in probability in betting games, as well as from De-Finetti, and from finance—many inspirations abound. Imagine the Sceptic selling the variable $x$ to some opponent, what price can this Sceptic charge for $x$? Here’s the same question posed differently: imagine you own a black-box with certain reward in it. You cannot see inside the box, but can posit certain idea what might be inside the box. The opponent comes to buy the box, and in the process of selling this black-box to this opponent, you’re committing to give this opponent what might be inside the box (that you don’t know of, but have certain hypothesis). What price you’d charge, so that the transaction doesn’t put you under risk (or loss)? In our case, the variable $x$ is the said black-box—it is the black-box precisely because the vakue of $x$ is dictated by the world $\xi \in \Omega$ which is out of control of the Sceptic. 

The answer to the above question is obvious in one case. Imagine a situation when the agent has no whatsover idea about what might be inside the black-box. If the agent doesn’t want to impose themselves to the risk in selling this black-box to the opponent, and to commit to pay or cover for what might be inside the black-box, then clearly it makes to ask $\sup_{\xi \in \Omega}x\left(\xi\right)$ as a payment from the opponent. But as per the scientific approach outlined above, the Sceptic also has to specify price in such a way that signals their understanding of the phenomena, as the Sceptic is not just selling the black-box but the claim that they have certain understanding of what might be inside the black-box. And this is where comes the second elegant move in the game-theoretic framework. 

If the Sceptic’s theory can predict what the World is going to do next, then it can be claimed that the Sceptic understands the World. In the game-theoretic framework, this is formalised by the Sceptic having a certain strategy $\mathcal{P}$ to predict what the World is going to next, where the prediction is replaced by betting. That is the Sceptic actively bets as per the strategy $\mathcal{P}$ as to what the World will do next. This leads to the game-setup as defined below:

- Sceptic starts with some initial wealth $K_0$, and the strategy $\mathcal{P}$
- for $t=1,2,3, \ldots$
    - Sceptic puts certain stake $m_t$ using the strategy $\mathcal{P}$
    - The World reveals $y_t$
    - The capital of the Sceptic changes to $K^{\mathcal{P}}_t = K^{\mathcal{P}}_{t-1} + m_t \cdot y_t$

To elaborate further, at each round $t$, the Sceptic puts some stake defined by the strategy towards the outcome (tide or no-tide), and $K_{t}^{\mathcal{P}}$ denotes the accumulated capital so far. If the Sceptic’s strategy of betting aligns with the World’s moves, then the Sceptic is able to increase the wealth. Once the World has revealed the complete move path $\xi$ (and we can assume for now that the game terminates at some time step), then the final capital of the Sceptic is $K^{\mathcal{P}}(\xi)$. The problem is that the World’s moves are independent of what the Sceptic does or think, and the Sceptic’s behaviour is defined by the strategy $\mathcal{P}$, to to be able to be recognised as a good strategy, the Sceptic needs to ensure:

                                                                                               $K^{\mathcal{P}}(\xi) \geq x\left(\xi\right) - \text{[something]}, \quad \forall \xi \in \Omega$. 

Let’s unpack the above expression to see what $\text{[something]}$ will be: as stated before $x$ is the black-box whose value is determined by how the World turns out to be, i.e. $\xi$, and hence when the Sceptic is committing to sell $x$ to the opponent, they will have to give them $x(\xi)$ and since $\xi$ is not known, the commitment binds the Sceptic to pay $x(\xi)$ for all possible realisations of $\xi$. Given the strategy $K^{\mathcal{P}}(\xi)$ denotes how much capital the Sceptic can accumulate if the World turns out to be in the state $\xi$. The Sceptic is concerned with the price to charge the opponent so that the commitment goes through for any $\xi \in \Omega$. The above expression then says that using the strategy $\mathcal{P}$ (that signals the understanding of the World), the Sceptic should be able to generate as much capital so that the commitment goes through, and hence that $\text{[something]}$ denotes the price the Sceptic needs to charge. Denote the price to be $\alpha$, then the same expression re-written is 

                                                                                          $K^{\mathcal{P}}(\xi) \geq x\left(\xi\right) - \alpha, \quad \forall \xi \in \Omega$,

thereby the expression says that the Sceptic call sell the black-box $x$ to the opponent for the price $\alpha$, and is confident in their understanding of the World (i.e. $\mathcal{P}$) so that the transaction can go through without putting the Sceptic at risk (or loss). To contrast with the setting where the Sceptic had no clue about the World whatsoever, and the price specified was $\sup_{\xi \in \Omega}x\left(\xi\right)$: this price allows the Sceptic to let the commitment go through without putting the Sceptic at risk. In the above case with the strategy $\mathcal{P}$, the Sceptic can specify the price lower than $\alpha$ as they can generate enough capital by themselves that wouldn’t put them at risk. The better the understanding of the World,